The Susceptible–Infected–Recovered (SIR) model is formulated for epidemiology models which present the terminology, notation, and standard outcomes. Epidemic model is utilized to portray rapid outbreaks that happen in less than one year, while the endemic model is utilized for examining infections over prolonged periods, during which there is a reestablishment of defenseless by births or recuperation from transitory immunity. The classic SIR model gives a natural premise to seeing more intricate epidemiology modeling results [2]. The model equations of SIR, where S, I, and R stand for the number of susceptible, infected, and removed individuals (either recovered or died), respectively, are defined as follows:8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
